However, the sequence length \( n \) can vary from 1 to 10, so we need to consider the sum of the number of sequences for each possible length. The number of sequences of length \( n \) is \((n + 1)^{10}\) because each element has \( n + 1 \) choices (never included or included starting at each of the \( n \) positions). Therefore, the total number of sequences \( K \) is the sum of \((n + 1)^{10}\) for \( n \) from 1 to 10: \[ K = \sum_{n=1}^{10} (n + 1)^{10} \] We need to compute this sum modulo 10.
